---
import BaseLayout from 'src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            color: #333;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }

        .container {
            width: 80%;
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 30px auto;
            padding: 20px;
            background: #fff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        h1 {
            color: #2c3e50;
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
        }

        h2 {
            color: #34495e;
            margin-top: 25px;
        }

        code {
            background: #f8f9fa;
            padding: 2px 5px;
            border-radius: 3px;
            font-family: monospace;
        }

        .code-block {
            background: #f8f9fa;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            margin: 15px 0;
            overflow-x: auto;
        }
    </style>

    <div class="container">
        <a href="/bloglist" style="display: inline-block; margin-bottom: 20px; text-decoration: none; color: #3498db;">&larr; Back</a>
        <h1>Java Basics</h1>
        
        <h2>Introduction to Java</h2>
        <p>Java is a class-based, object-oriented programming language designed to be platform-independent.</p>

        <h2>Basic Syntax</h2>
        <div class="code-block">
            <code> <pre>

                {`public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
        }
        }`}
        </pre>
            </code>
        </div>

        <h2>Variables and Data Types</h2>
        <p>Java has several basic data types:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><code>int</code> - Integer values</li>
            <li><code>double</code> - Decimal numbers</li>
            <li><code>boolean</code> - True/false values</li>
            <li><code>String</code> - Text values</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Control Structures</h2>
        <p>Java supports standard control structures:</p>
        <div class="code-block">
            <code><pre>

                {`// If statement
if (condition) {
    
} else {
    
}

// For loop
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    
}

// While loop
while (condition) {
    
}`}
        </pre>
            </code>
        </div>

        <h2>Object-Oriented Programming</h2>
        <p>Java is built around classes and objects. Here's a simple class example:</p>
        <div class="code-block">
            <code>
                <pre>
{`class Car {
    String model;
    int year;
    
    public Car(String model, int year) {
        this.model = model;
        this.year = year;
    }
}`}
            </pre></code>
        </div>

        <footer>
            <p>&copy; 2024 Learn2Code | Empowering beginners to dive into programming</p>
        </footer>
    </div>
</BaseLayout>
